    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="402"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A14/695</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Persia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hornibrook</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 45</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-28">August 28,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to previous correspondence
                    regarding the activities of the Persian Minister in Washington in connection
                    with the ratification by the United States of the Arms Traffic Convention signed
                    at Geneva in 1925, there is enclosed a copy of a note which the Minister
                    addressed to the Secretary of State on August 11, 1934.<note n="55"
                        xml:id="d402fn55">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_471">p. 471</ref>.</note> The
                    general tone of this communication is so obviously improper and it contains so
                    many misleading statements and misstatements that the Secretary considered <pb
                        facs="0584" n="484" xml:id="pg_484"/> it necessary to send the Minister a
                    reply under date of August 24, of which a copy is enclosed.<note n="56"
                        xml:id="d402fn56">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_481">p. 481</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You may on a suitable occasion, if you consider that any useful purpose would be
                    served, refer casually to the substance of the Secretary’s present
                    communication, in conversation with competent Persian officials.</p>
                <p>There are also transmitted, for the information of the Legation, a copy of a
                    letter which the Minister addressed to me on August 21,<note n="57"
                        xml:id="d402fn57">Not printed.</note> as well as a copy of a note which he
                    sent to the Secretary on August 25<note n="58" xml:id="d402fn58">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note> in reply to the Secretary’s note of August 24.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
